WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.100 --> 00:00:06.410
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Great.

00:00:06.410 --> 00:00:11.990
I'm very happy to introduce Tomas Sedlacek,
the author of The Economics of Good and Evil.

00:00:11.990 --> 00:00:14.820
He
teaches at Charles University and is a member

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:17.650
of the
National Economic Council in Prague.

00:00:17.650 --> 00:00:19.800
He's worked as an
advisor to VÃ¡clav Havel.

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:23.530
He's going to take us on a
whirlwind tour of intellectual history, from

00:00:23.530 --> 00:00:27.510
the epic of
Gilgamesh to the Hebrew Bible, to Greek philosophers,

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:31.080
the New Testament, the medieval period, Mandeville,
Hume,

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:35.530
Adam Smith, Marx, points at the many stories
in

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:37.219
economics that don't show up in the formulas,
but still

00:00:37.219 --> 00:00:39.359
resonate in people's lives.

00:00:39.359 --> 00:00:43.429
We've over-mathematized, and
so missed important philosophical issues that

00:00:43.429 --> 00:00:45.159
are
hidden in the formulas that would rather be

00:00:45.159 --> 00:00:48.160
precisely
wrong than roughly correct, or which mistake

00:00:48.160 --> 00:00:50.760
beauty for
truth in Krugman's phrase.

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:53.481
It's time to remember the
alternative stories to get us out of the mess

00:00:53.481 --> 00:00:54.481
we're in.

00:00:54.481 --> 00:00:55.559
It's time to realize that invisible hands
and

00:00:55.559 --> 00:01:00.100
equilibrium are every bit as much myths as
unicorns and

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:01.100
dragons.

00:01:01.100 --> 00:01:05.210
They may be useful for a story, but they need
to be taken with a big grain of salt.

00:01:05.210 --> 00:01:07.939
Please join me in
welcoming Tomas Sedlacek.

00:01:07.939 --> 00:01:11.630
[Clapping]
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: So thank you.

00:01:11.630 --> 00:01:15.439
It's a great pleasure
to be here with you today and let's really

00:01:15.439 --> 00:01:19.329
do this quite
quickly, and let's try and see how far we

00:01:19.329 --> 00:01:23.720
can go down
the history of Economics of Good and Evil.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:24.720
Okay.

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:26.170
So
one of my basic points is that we've never

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:27.460
separated the
two.

00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:36.350
It was always economics and morality being
connected really together, not -- well, with

00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:39.990
Adam Smith
being sort of a climax of the debate; Adam

00:01:39.990 --> 00:01:44.119
Smith did not
really start this whole notion of economics,

00:01:44.119 --> 00:01:47.390
but Adam
Smith was a moral philosopher, and so was

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:49.720
Hume, and so
were actually all the classical philosopher

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.539
-- I mean
economists were basically philosophers.

00:01:52.539 --> 00:01:56.549
Now, what I
think is one of the struggle and the trouble

00:01:56.549 --> 00:02:02.020
we have today
in 2011 is that we view these two words absolutely

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:03.020
separate.

00:02:03.020 --> 00:02:09.819
We have this impersonal, technical,
math-looking ideology of the free market that

00:02:09.819 --> 00:02:15.860
simply
runs like an engine, like a robot, and is

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:21.250
value free,
allegedly, is absolutely inhuman, it's just

00:02:21.250 --> 00:02:23.030
like a
machine.

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:27.230
And that's why we treat it with calculus,
that's how we treat it with all sorts of mechanistic

00:02:27.230 --> 00:02:30.390
approaches, as if it was a computer program,
as if it

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:34.590
was a stimulation of work.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:41.610
And that strange body,
zombie, that does not really have a soul -- we

00:02:41.610 --> 00:02:44.170
made it
to look like it doesn't have a soul -- produces

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:47.650
results
that we don't really like.

00:02:47.650 --> 00:02:53.200
And of course if you look
down on the best selling books on Amazon or

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.750
at any
bookstore, it would all be books that are

00:02:55.750 --> 00:02:59.620
critical on
economy.

00:02:59.620 --> 00:03:01.930
Where did we go wrong, the animal spirits,
the

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:03.810
myths of the rational market, you can go on.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:06.260
You can
actually go through all the books that you

00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:09.500
see on the
best selling list and you will not find one

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:13.760
that goes
praising the economy for whatever good that

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:15.070
we have
around us.

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:20.430
So it is disjointed, it creates results that
we're not happy with.

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:24.310
On the other hand, we have moral
expectations that the market is going to solve

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:26.310
everything, it's going to make everybody happy,
and

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:28.120
everybody better off.

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:35.110
So the problem was or is what we
had together is now disjointed.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:41.950
So you know in the book
of Job in the Old Testament it says "Should

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:44.680
I only
accept from the hand of the Lord the good

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:48.710
things and not
the bad things?" and I think we have a similar

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:51.580
--
similar guiding narrative when it comes to

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:55.690
this myth of
the market is supposed to do everything right.

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:58.020
So the
markets in a way are either hated and they

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:01.680
are the cause
of all problems as we have quotes in the New

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:05.260
Testament
and other spiritual sources that there is

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:08.600
a huge divide
between money, and money is the root of all

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.800
evil --
which is a misquote by the way, but never

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:16.769
mind and then
we have this spiritual, soft, human, wishy

00:04:16.769 --> 00:04:21.630
washy zone of
life, and this one is supposed to correct

00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:25.870
the doings of
this machine called the market.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.310
So in practical
application you have the government, which

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:32.590
is supposed
to, the story goes, soften the results of

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:35.990
the market,
but these two are disjointed, they're not

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:41.940
together
anymore, and that's where kind of the problem

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:45.640
comes
from.

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:56.180
Now, the remedy is not in correcting the -- so
okay.

00:04:56.180 --> 00:04:59.260
Let's go into mythology.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:03.080
If you look on all
myths that we have around us or if you look

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:05.960
at horror
stories, there are basically two things that

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:07.160
we fear.

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:10.070
We fear when the body and soul gets disjointed.

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:11.190
All
right?

00:05:11.190 --> 00:05:13.290
So if you get the body disjointed from the
soul,

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:15.900
you get zombies on the one hand, or you get
ghosts and

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:17.180
spirits on the other.

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:22.150
The thing doesn't work very well
if it's -- if it's disjointed.

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:26.920
Also mark that if you go
and analyze all the myths and -- including

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:31.550
modern myths,
we fear two things.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:39.360
When a human being is mixed with an
animal, vampire, werewolf, all sorts of wizards

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:41.930
that
live in the forest and they have animal-like

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:46.590
behavior on
the one hand; and then there's another guarding

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.700
fear,
really, that we have, and that is that of

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:52.040
robots.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.260
You
see that in Matrix, you see that in the War

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:56.260
of the
Worlds.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:57.920
So, how to read this.

00:05:57.920 --> 00:06:02.220
I think this is exactly
the same area.

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:06.020
We've disjointed something that should
have been together, body and soul.

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:09.020
You disjoint that,
you get horror figures that we are afraid

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:11.970
of, tremendous
fear out of these things.

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:16.440
They look like human beings,
zombies for example, but they act like animals.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:21.110
They
eat, I mean, the common narrative of all zombie

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:24.419
stories
is this used to be my wife; or my friend;

00:06:24.419 --> 00:06:31.200
or my father;
suddenly he, or she, or it ceases to be human,

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:33.860
it
becomes an animal, and it attacks you, and

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:37.710
it treats you
as if you were just a piece of meat.

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:45.780
And the other
problem is that of human beings becoming machine-like.

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:47.390
So how do we read this economically?

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:51.160
I think the moment
you start disjoining these two, you get into

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:56.021
a
catastrophe situation, which is the place

00:06:56.021 --> 00:06:58.180
of a human
being is always to be together.

00:06:58.180 --> 00:07:04.930
A rational,
mathematical way of thinking needs to be part

00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:09.370
of human,
but it mustn't be only that.

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:13.080
These are all the
Hitler-like characters.

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:18.280
You saw quite nicely in the
last movie, for example, Avatar, you have

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:21.850
this soldier
who only wants profit, who calculates who

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:25.770
doesn't care
for who he kills while he does that.

00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:27.110
So that's a true
horror figure.

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:32.480
And, on the other hand, you have these
animalistic -- animal spirit tendencies.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:37.550
So as an
economist, you can see one extreme being homoeconomicus,

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:45.610
rational, calculating, mathematical, cold,
calculus of

00:07:45.610 --> 00:07:48.210
consumption and production, nothing else matters.

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:51.540
And
on the other hand animal spirits, which is

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:57.310
a concept
that John Maynard Keynes talked about in his

00:07:57.310 --> 00:08:02.370
general theory,
something that we economists fear but we don't

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:03.370
understand.

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:04.370
It's a singularity.

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:10.070
It's an animal that
reacts, that propels us forward, that's adventurous,

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:13.340
but
it's not controlled by reason.

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:17.889
So you can see this fear
when you disjoin two things that should be

00:08:17.889 --> 00:08:22.350
together, and
I argue that this is exactly what happened

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:23.350
with the
economy.

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:24.690
We got ridiculous results with the market
that

00:08:24.690 --> 00:08:30.750
nobody really likes, often, and we have ridiculous
expectations that really can't be matched

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:35.240
by anybody
else except for maybe God or maybe a host

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:38.869
of gods;
definitely not the market.

00:08:38.869 --> 00:08:41.490
So that's one way of looking
at it.

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:47.730
Let me take another fly through -- fly through
the history of economy, and maybe because

00:08:47.730 --> 00:08:51.720
I am speaking
in the premises of Google, maybe answer the

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:56.110
question why
Plato would love Google.

00:08:56.110 --> 00:08:57.360
Okay.

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:03.180
So if we actually go
fast forward the history of the economy, you

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:05.920
will learn
that it was -- in the beginning it was important

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:09.779
to
actually master material things such as acts,

00:09:09.779 --> 00:09:14.680
and be
close to sources of iron, or maybe salt, or

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:18.269
be at the
cross roads of a passage that people had to

00:09:18.269 --> 00:09:20.629
pass
through, or information you had to pass through,

00:09:20.629 --> 00:09:23.230
or --
but more likely material things that you had

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:24.230
to pass
through.

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:28.180
That was the time of matter, where matter
mattered the most.

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:32.009
Then we had the time of
manufacturing where it wasn't all that important

00:09:32.009 --> 00:09:35.040
where
that thing -- there we go.

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:38.380
Advertisements are falling
apart.

00:09:38.380 --> 00:09:43.579
What kind of a world are we living in?

00:09:43.579 --> 00:09:44.980
Founding
superstructure.

00:09:44.980 --> 00:09:49.230
Manufacturing, it wasn't really
important where you got the stuff from, but

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:56.310
the nations
that owned companies -- I mean, owned manufacturing

00:09:56.310 --> 00:10:03.629
infrastruc- -- I mean, yeah, manufacturers,
that's where

00:10:03.629 --> 00:10:06.290
Ford's T-time.

00:10:06.290 --> 00:10:08.480
. These nations were the rich nations.

00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:15.000
We move from that from a -- from things, from
things to

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.730
thinks, where thinking was important.

00:10:18.730 --> 00:10:22.709
This was the time
of lawyers, this was the time of accountants,

00:10:22.709 --> 00:10:24.880
this was
the time of advisors.

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:31.839
And eventually we are moving into
the area, I argue, of non-things where -- and

00:10:31.839 --> 00:10:38.379
I think this
is the time where we actually witness is thinking,

00:10:38.379 --> 00:10:43.420
planning, doing things rigorously is no longer
important.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:50.059
What's important is the soft skills and
moving into further level of abstractness.

00:10:50.059 --> 00:10:54.040
Let me give
an example of three titans -- let me get rid

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:56.390
of this --
of three titans of the past.

00:10:56.390 --> 00:11:00.970
One was actually IBM which
you know you could actually knock on the product

00:11:00.970 --> 00:11:04.880
of IBM
and you had to ship it, and you owned a piece

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:06.319
of matter.

00:11:06.319 --> 00:11:09.019
If you tried really hard you could turn it
into an ax or

00:11:09.019 --> 00:11:11.689
something else; it was matter.

00:11:11.689 --> 00:11:14.050
Second generation was
Microsoft.

00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:22.720
Now, the product of Microsoft is extremely
abstract; you can't really knock on it, but

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:26.790
at least you
can put it in a box and you can sell it, and

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.600
you can
come home and you can say to your family,

00:11:28.600 --> 00:11:33.339
"Look, I
bought a new product by Microsoft" for example.

00:11:33.339 --> 00:11:40.649
Okay,
and third in this legion of titans is Google,

00:11:40.649 --> 00:11:43.930
where you
can't really box Google.

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:48.139
That's absolutely absurd
thought.

00:11:48.139 --> 00:11:55.529
You can't actually buy anything from Google,
and the wonderful trick is while Microsoft

00:11:55.529 --> 00:12:02.110
is trying to
employ people and pay them for doing things

00:12:02.110 --> 00:12:06.749
for it,
Google does it exactly the other way around.

00:12:06.749 --> 00:12:09.170
It employs
people voluntarily.

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:14.819
So you guys have millions of
employees uploading things to YouTube, putting

00:12:14.819 --> 00:12:20.709
things on
also Wikipedia is running down the same logic,

00:12:20.709 --> 00:12:25.499
where you
absolutely conquered the whole idea of matter.

00:12:25.499 --> 00:12:29.290
What's
wonderful is the thing that you can't look

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:34.119
for in
Google -- once I had high fever and I was

00:12:34.119 --> 00:12:36.490
at home and I
was looking for a particular book, a physical

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:37.490
book,
okay.

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:40.610
That was in the times that books were actually
printed in paper.

00:12:40.610 --> 00:12:44.529
And I was looking through my study
and I couldn't find the book, and as I was

00:12:44.529 --> 00:12:47.170
in my high
fevers I thought okay, well, I'll just Google

00:12:47.170 --> 00:12:48.910
it.

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:51.220
Google -- the trick of Google is it will not
find

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:53.160
anything real.

00:12:53.160 --> 00:12:57.629
All the things that you deal with is
information, and of course it has a value

00:12:57.629 --> 00:13:00.430
of its own,
but it's not real, it's not really anything

00:13:00.430 --> 00:13:04.529
that you can
knock on or you can actually situate or localize.

00:13:04.529 --> 00:13:08.649
And
this is why I think the original idea of the

00:13:08.649 --> 00:13:13.269
mind
conquering the matter kind of materializes

00:13:13.269 --> 00:13:17.079
in our
generation in the development of Google where

00:13:17.079 --> 00:13:22.340
you
actually create sort of a rule, an upload

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:26.739
space such as
YouTube or the Internet, and then you live

00:13:26.739 --> 00:13:35.309
as the gate
to this enumerable chaos.

00:13:35.309 --> 00:13:39.050
That I think is something
where we will go forward.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:44.769
One last thought and then
I'll be ready to take your questions in this.

00:13:44.769 --> 00:13:48.299
Nietzsche
wrote about the age of a child.

00:13:48.299 --> 00:13:52.239
He says, "In the
development of a human being, we have three

00:13:52.239 --> 00:13:53.239
ages.

00:13:53.239 --> 00:13:54.630
One
age is the age of a camel.

00:13:54.630 --> 00:14:01.879
Now, a camel takes upon
himself heavy burdens and wants to travel

00:14:01.879 --> 00:14:09.889
or travels
through dry deserts without water and is actually

00:14:09.889 --> 00:14:12.589
enslaved for a purpose of somebody else.

00:14:12.589 --> 00:14:15.350
Then you have
an age of a lion.

00:14:15.350 --> 00:14:22.220
Lion fights, and rebels, and attacks
everything in the surrounding, and it is impossible

00:14:22.220 --> 00:14:25.130
to
saddle him and impossible to tell him to walk

00:14:25.130 --> 00:14:26.740
on and
serve somebody else.

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:28.639
It doesn't lend towards it.

00:14:28.639 --> 00:14:31.980
And
the third age is the age of the child.

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:35.370
The child is
playful, the child doesn't t really worry

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:38.610
about
anything, the child wants to be educated,

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:40.939
the child
wants to learn, the child wants to stand in

00:14:40.939 --> 00:14:41.939
awe.

00:14:41.939 --> 00:14:45.920
Now, I
think this is one other way how we could actually

00:14:45.920 --> 00:14:48.569
read -- and Nietzsche had this under personal
development,

00:14:48.569 --> 00:14:51.129
but it's easy to see how we can apply this
into the

00:14:51.129 --> 00:14:56.860
development of our day and age where the whole
thing

00:14:56.860 --> 00:15:03.410
with iPod, for example, is the advantage of
an iPod is

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:04.779
that it's fun.

00:15:04.779 --> 00:15:11.060
A small child can operate it and it is
not serious, it is not meant to be serious,

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:16.589
and this is
what's beautiful about [pause] this is what's

00:15:16.589 --> 00:15:20.389
beautiful
about Google.

00:15:20.389 --> 00:15:25.760
It is -- for many people it's the gateway
into the chaos of Internet, but the page itself

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:27.959
is
empty.

00:15:27.959 --> 00:15:31.529
It's a white page, which we just saw, and
the

00:15:31.529 --> 00:15:35.439
only thing you have there is a line where
you, yourself,

00:15:35.439 --> 00:15:39.160
type the way you like it.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:43.480
And this is something, a direction, into
which we are moving.

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:48.730
Who would have thought 20 years
ago that you can make any money on searching

00:15:48.730 --> 00:15:49.730
in the
Internet?

00:15:49.730 --> 00:15:53.541
You're not even providing Internet access,
you're not providing Internet space, you're

00:15:53.541 --> 00:15:56.839
not
computers, you're not providing anything except

00:15:56.839 --> 00:15:57.839
for
searching.

00:15:57.839 --> 00:16:05.629
And the searching also we can look at it
from a completely opposite view.

00:16:05.629 --> 00:16:09.649
We think that we're
searching information where, in fact, we are

00:16:09.649 --> 00:16:12.509
searching
the 'not'.

00:16:12.509 --> 00:16:18.749
Because what Google does, it filters out all
the things that you don't want to know.

00:16:18.749 --> 00:16:26.149
There was a
medieval monk, Meister Eckhart -- you've probably

00:16:26.149 --> 00:16:30.069
heard
of him -- and when he was asked what will

00:16:30.069 --> 00:16:36.100
burn us in
hell, he said, "In hell, it will be the not,

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:37.809
the
negative that is burning."

00:16:37.809 --> 00:16:43.149
In other words, my hand will
burn from coal only because my hand is not

00:16:43.149 --> 00:16:44.559
coal.

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:47.239
So
everything in my hand that is not coal, burns.

00:16:47.239 --> 00:16:52.079
If my
hand was made of coal, then you could torture

00:16:52.079 --> 00:16:56.129
me as you
want, but it would not hurt me because it

00:16:56.129 --> 00:16:57.129
is the not.

00:16:57.129 --> 00:16:59.759
It is the difference, it is the gap between
these two

00:16:59.759 --> 00:17:01.649
elements that is burning.

00:17:01.649 --> 00:17:06.389
Similar, Google actually
filters out the 'not' more than it actually

00:17:06.389 --> 00:17:09.610
looks for the
things that you want to do.

00:17:09.610 --> 00:17:14.730
So the economy is
becoming -- and this is I think one way to

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:16.990
contemplate
about where the future is developing, and

00:17:16.990 --> 00:17:22.669
it's
developing from things through thinks, rationality,

00:17:22.669 --> 00:17:27.929
to
non-thinks, to personalization, to emotional

00:17:27.929 --> 00:17:32.380
enjoyment,
to playfulness, and these, I think, will be

00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:36.220
the products
in the future that will gain the attention

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:37.360
of customers.

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:42.460
And surprisingly this emancipation of economy
from

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:48.820
matter to pure mind jumping over the rational
period is

00:17:48.820 --> 00:17:50.640
something that we're witnessing today.

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:57.040
In my book, I
touch upon subjects such as these.

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:01.991
I start with the
epic of Gilgamesh only to show that there

00:18:01.991 --> 00:18:06.010
is a lot of
economic thinking in ancient myth.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:11.710
You can go down any
basic three founding cultures that we have

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:15.870
in Europe and
America, which is the Old Testament, the Greeks,

00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:21.360
Christianity, and the Sumerian mythology,
which was a

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:23.240
founding inspiration for a lot of the Greeks
and a lot

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:25.130
of the Hebrews.

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:29.460
So the first half of the book talks
about economics and mythology, and the second

00:18:29.460 --> 00:18:34.950
half talks
about mythology in modern economics.

00:18:34.950 --> 00:18:37.610
What do we believe
today as economists?

00:18:37.610 --> 00:18:43.500
And let me just give you one
example of an ancient story which explains

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:48.260
current
situation maybe better than all these models

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:51.429
that we
have.

00:18:51.429 --> 00:18:57.220
It's -- [INAUDIBLE] -- I don't know if you...
we

00:18:57.220 --> 00:19:00.750
now are witnessing what we call a business
cycle.

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:03.559
It's
the most recent business cycle.

00:19:03.559 --> 00:19:10.409
So it's always useful
to ask for the oldest ever business cycle.

00:19:10.409 --> 00:19:12.260
Anything
comes to your mind?

00:19:12.260 --> 00:19:18.000
The oldest business cycle in
recorded history of mankind.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:33.380
&gt;&gt;Male #1: [INAUDIBLE]
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Yeah.

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:35.500
But a business cycle proper.

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:41.190
&gt;&gt;Male #1 [INAUDIBLE]
TOMAS: There you go.

00:19:41.190 --> 00:19:47.240
This is in the old
testament where Pharaoh has a dream, and he

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:52.110
dreams about
seven fat deers -- seven fat cows, if you

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:53.139
recall, and
seven thin cows.

00:19:53.139 --> 00:19:57.039
That is the oldest business cycle
proper.

00:19:57.039 --> 00:20:02.510
Here's grain, GDP as we probably say today.

00:20:02.510 --> 00:20:05.720
We have
seven years of surplus, and seven years of

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:06.720
famine.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:12.130
Now,
Pharaoh immediately asks Joseph okay, what

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:13.130
am I to do
with this?

00:20:13.130 --> 00:20:18.640
This is obviously a situation, and how do
I

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:19.830
deal with it?

00:20:19.830 --> 00:20:28.029
And Joseph, because he read Keynes a lot
when he was younger, gives him an answer.

00:20:28.029 --> 00:20:34.279
Well, in the
good years, do not eat everything that grows.

00:20:34.279 --> 00:20:43.190
Save your
energy and build silos -- I mean, store houses.

00:20:43.190 --> 00:20:47.000
So it's
a form of consumer energy that you don't use.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.830
In other
words, you could be on this level of joy -- or

00:20:49.830 --> 00:20:54.870
consumption, but do not eat it all.

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:59.419
Decrease your
consumption here so that in the bad years

00:20:59.419 --> 00:21:03.789
you can
increase your consumption from, I don't know

00:21:03.789 --> 00:21:10.090
-X to a
level which you can survive at.

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:13.130
This level of
consumption we were all dying; this level

00:21:13.130 --> 00:21:16.470
of consumption
we can survive.

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:21.000
So what's the lesson to take from this
story?

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:25.350
First of all, the role of economist never
was

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:29.259
increase of GDP growth.

00:21:29.259 --> 00:21:35.159
It was only in the times of
crises when we are to increase GDP growth

00:21:35.159 --> 00:21:38.409
from let's say
-20 to -7.

00:21:38.409 --> 00:21:46.850
Incidentally, by the way, in the year 2008,
if we had balanced budget -- if you guys in

00:21:46.850 --> 00:21:53.059
America had
a balanced budget, your GDP would be -23 percent.

00:21:53.059 --> 00:21:57.470
Now,
the number itself isn't important.

00:21:57.470 --> 00:22:00.380
What's important is
that nobody asks this question.

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:06.190
So we consider whatever
growth, no matter how much debt-induced it

00:22:06.190 --> 00:22:09.970
is, to be a
true, healthy, natural level of growth.

00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:12.240
But in fact
we're just dealing with energy.

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:14.910
Energy and money travel
in time.

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:27.710
So this is, of course fiscal policy, you store
the energy, you run fiscal surpluses.

00:22:27.710 --> 00:22:31.380
That means you slow
down the economy, which is the role of the

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:32.380
economist.

00:22:32.380 --> 00:22:34.539
The role of the economist is decreasing the
amplitude of

00:22:34.539 --> 00:22:38.309
a business cycle, never, never in the long
run to

00:22:38.309 --> 00:22:43.419
increase GDP -- GDP growth, definitely not
by fiscal

00:22:43.419 --> 00:22:45.380
stimuli.

00:22:45.380 --> 00:22:49.080
And here you have fiscal deficits.

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:51.580
Okay.

00:22:51.580 --> 00:22:56.259
So
what did we do to bring it to some sort of

00:22:56.259 --> 00:23:00.390
a catharsis?

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:04.570
We also -- by the way, from the year 2001
with we had

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:08.730
the September 11 attacks, we had seven very
good years

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:12.370
that were bracketed by two very significant
events.

00:23:12.370 --> 00:23:15.820
This was one not only geopolitically, but
this was the

00:23:15.820 --> 00:23:18.740
year when America produced its last budget
surplus, this

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:22.870
is the year when Fed started the policy of
extremely low

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:25.429
interest rates, etc., etc.

00:23:25.429 --> 00:23:31.360
And the hike of the crises
was collapse of Lehman Brothers, which was

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:37.320
by the way,
2008, September 15th.

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:42.050
So of course I think this is just
a pure coincidence, but you see seven very

00:23:42.050 --> 00:23:44.830
good years
bracketed by two significant events.

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:48.690
Now, the question
is, what did we do with our fiscal policy

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:51.799
here?

00:23:51.799 --> 00:23:55.179
We did
exactly the opposite.

00:23:55.179 --> 00:23:59.010
Either we didn't do anything,
some countries just stayed on the level of

00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:03.490
debt that
they had before, but many countries, including

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:06.809
United
States, increased and was not running fiscal

00:24:06.809 --> 00:24:09.990
surpluses,
but was running fiscal deficits, in other

00:24:09.990 --> 00:24:15.620
words,
increasing GDP growth during good years.

00:24:15.620 --> 00:24:20.690
So not only did
we not save in the in the store houses, but

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:25.750
that
imaginary storehouse was full of IOUs.

00:24:25.750 --> 00:24:29.110
So we took the
energy -- and this is why there is such a

00:24:29.110 --> 00:24:33.559
huge, huge
divide here, and this is why the crisis is

00:24:33.559 --> 00:24:37.330
much deeper
than it should -- than it had to be, because

00:24:37.330 --> 00:24:41.590
we wasted
that energy boost during good years when we

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:45.400
didn't need
to do that at all and now when we want to

00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:50.460
boost the
economies, we are running into bankruptcies,

00:24:50.460 --> 00:24:53.779
not only in
Europe, but also here.

00:24:53.779 --> 00:24:56.590
So what's my point here?

00:24:56.590 --> 00:25:01.029
My
point here now is that we had similar situations,

00:25:01.029 --> 00:25:04.100
similar stories, back in the history 4,000,
3,000 years

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:05.100
ago.

00:25:05.100 --> 00:25:08.230
People were aware of it and they treated it
--

00:25:08.230 --> 00:25:10.549
instead of mathematical, apparently they treated
it with

00:25:10.549 --> 00:25:15.610
stories that a seven-year-old child could
understand.

00:25:15.610 --> 00:25:21.700
What's even more striking is that we -- well,
you could

00:25:21.700 --> 00:25:24.769
go as far as to say that we were blinded by
all the

00:25:24.769 --> 00:25:30.629
self-assuring mathematical models telling
us basically

00:25:30.629 --> 00:25:37.320
this, that we didn't -- it didn't -- Well,
the wisdom of

00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:41.549
this story, again, that a seven-year-old child
understands is something that we trespassed

00:25:41.549 --> 00:25:49.090
against and
we couldn't be wise enough to act at least

00:25:49.090 --> 00:25:54.200
the way
Pharaoh acted in the time where, you know,

00:25:54.200 --> 00:25:55.870
economic
studies were primitive.

00:25:55.870 --> 00:25:58.759
So there's still a lot of
things that we can learn from this.

00:25:58.759 --> 00:26:04.980
I think this is
exactly the rule that we should adopt also

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:05.980
in our
thinking.

00:26:05.980 --> 00:26:10.019
That means in good years target some level
of

00:26:10.019 --> 00:26:11.019
growth.

00:26:11.019 --> 00:26:13.429
Let's say we could have grown by 6 percent,
but

00:26:13.429 --> 00:26:19.179
we will only grow by 2, and this energy we
will

00:26:19.179 --> 00:26:22.929
recuperate so to speak so that we can use
it in the

00:26:22.929 --> 00:26:25.019
times of the crises.

00:26:25.019 --> 00:26:26.769
Yeah.

00:26:26.769 --> 00:26:32.039
I'll end here.

00:26:32.039 --> 00:26:33.940
Instead of
giving you an overview of the book, I think

00:26:33.940 --> 00:26:37.840
it's better
that I gave you these three stories that I

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:42.220
think are
sort of explaining or guarding the development

00:26:42.220 --> 00:26:43.300
of our
economic thought.

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:53.179
The first story was animal and human,
and we -- and robot, sorry, and we human beings

00:26:53.179 --> 00:26:55.789
have to
be in the middle.

00:26:55.789 --> 00:26:58.259
There will never be psychological
beasts.

00:26:58.259 --> 00:27:01.309
You will always have these two tendencies,
and

00:27:01.309 --> 00:27:08.160
also the economy, homoeconomicus and animal
spirits as

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:12.179
to inborn tendencies or market and ethics.

00:27:12.179 --> 00:27:15.820
We, if you
separate them, it becomes a horror.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:18.210
So that was the
first story.

00:27:18.210 --> 00:27:24.249
The second story from the book is the
economy going more and more abstract, more

00:27:24.249 --> 00:27:27.540
and more
playful, and less and less serious.

00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:35.090
And the third story
is the behavior of age and Asians when it

00:27:35.090 --> 00:27:39.409
came to
business cycles and a comparison of how we

00:27:39.409 --> 00:27:43.830
foolishly
from this point of view behave today.

00:27:43.830 --> 00:27:47.480
So thank you for
your attention, and let's move into the debate,

00:27:47.480 --> 00:27:48.480
please.

