00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:29.000
anti-cyclical , so to speak, of growth.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.520
So when it grows,
yeah.

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:33.800
I've already explained that.

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:37.700
So that's another
way how to just you know get the discretion

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:39.150
out of it.

00:47:39.150 --> 00:47:43.660
And of course it will be still question for
politicians

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:44.760
who to tax.

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:45.760
Do I tax the poor?

00:47:45.760 --> 00:47:46.760
Do I tax the rich?

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:47.760
Do
I tax the successful?

00:47:47.760 --> 00:47:49.600
Do I tax the unsuccessful?

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:51.710
This
is a political debate and it must remain a

00:47:51.710 --> 00:47:54.610
political
debate.

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:56.570
And the other question is, who do I give the
money to?

00:47:56.570 --> 00:48:00.490
Do I support the poor or do I support the
rich?

00:48:00.490 --> 00:48:02.880
Do I support the successful, or do I support
the

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:03.880
unsuccessful?

00:48:03.880 --> 00:48:05.490
Do I support the strong, or do I support
the weak?

00:48:05.490 --> 00:48:07.090
Those are good questions.

00:48:07.090 --> 00:48:11.490
They're not easily
answered and they should remain political.

00:48:11.490 --> 00:48:13.860
What
shouldn't happen in the meantime is that politicians

00:48:13.860 --> 00:48:15.410
get
to print.

00:48:15.410 --> 00:48:17.820
I tax little, I give out a lot.

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:19.900
How can I do
this trick?

00:48:19.900 --> 00:48:22.010
Well, this is called debt.

00:48:22.010 --> 00:48:27.110
This -- so you
collect money and you print 20 percent more,

00:48:27.110 --> 00:48:28.110
and you
give it out.

00:48:28.110 --> 00:48:30.850
This print of 20 percent more should be
confiscated.

00:48:30.850 --> 00:48:38.090
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Given that politicians lie, I mean,
the

00:48:38.090 --> 00:48:40.260
Greek problem in large part was they had some
rules as

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:41.810
far as what they could do --
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: [soda spraying] Whoa.

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:46.380
&gt;&gt;Male #4: And they had big bang -- they had
big

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:49.180
banks help them --
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Big bangs, or big banks?

00:48:49.180 --> 00:48:50.180
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Big banks --
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Okay.

00:48:50.180 --> 00:48:51.180
&gt;&gt;Male #4: -- help them cheat.

00:48:51.180 --> 00:48:52.180
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Right.

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:53.890
&gt;&gt;Male #4: And politicians will always cheat
if they

00:48:53.890 --> 00:48:58.470
can because the -- the last stoic politician
died

00:48:58.470 --> 00:49:00.560
probably about 500 years ago.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:03.130
We all have really stupid
epicureans running the place.

00:49:03.130 --> 00:49:04.130
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Yeah.

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:06.000
&gt;&gt;Male #4: So how do you keep them from lying?

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:07.820
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Then you shouldn't put your hopes
up

00:49:07.820 --> 00:49:13.410
into electing a politician who is honest and
sincere,

00:49:13.410 --> 00:49:16.570
and good, and good meaning, and faithful,
and truthful.

00:49:16.570 --> 00:49:20.460
Instead, change the system so it doesn't matter
if he or

00:49:20.460 --> 00:49:21.460
she is thus.

00:49:21.460 --> 00:49:28.130
In other words, if you take this tool away
from them, you can have an idiot who will

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:29.530
not be able to
do harm.

00:49:29.530 --> 00:49:33.290
Do you know what I mean?

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:38.660
I have no -- I
have -- so I think all of us suffer Messianic

00:49:38.660 --> 00:49:39.660
Complex.

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:42.190
We believe somebody should come and take things
in

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:43.510
control.

00:49:43.510 --> 00:49:47.420
Some sort of a messiah, a
politician who is as you describe, honest

00:49:47.420 --> 00:49:48.540
and sincere.

00:49:48.540 --> 00:49:53.760
Well, he's not coming, or he didn't come for
a long

00:49:53.760 --> 00:49:57.660
time, and even Jesus, who was expected to
do this, to be

00:49:57.660 --> 00:50:02.330
a political messiah, didn't play that role
intentionally .

00:50:02.330 --> 00:50:04.700
He was not a political messiah.

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:08.451
So my answer is,
instead of hoping for better people, let's

00:50:08.451 --> 00:50:14.210
just create a
better system where you do not leave that

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:16.440
to a
discretion of people.

00:50:16.440 --> 00:50:21.910
You don't allow this propensity.

00:50:21.910 --> 00:50:28.580
&gt;&gt;Male #5: What you seem to be going for if
we don't

00:50:28.580 --> 00:50:32.940
go with the fiscal council, which would be
hard to do in

00:50:32.940 --> 00:50:36.940
this country, one would would hope because
it's pretty

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:41.611
antidemocratic and relies on people of privilege
and

00:50:41.611 --> 00:50:46.290
such, but if we go with the formula --
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: We already have that in monetary

00:50:46.290 --> 00:50:47.290
policy.

00:50:47.290 --> 00:50:48.730
&gt;&gt;Male #5: We do, and there are a lot of people
that

00:50:48.730 --> 00:50:49.730
are unhappy about that.

00:50:49.730 --> 00:50:51.130
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: But should we give it back to
politicians?

00:50:51.130 --> 00:50:52.349
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Okay.

00:50:52.349 --> 00:50:56.790
But it sounds like to go with the
formula, whether or not the formula is enforced

00:50:56.790 --> 00:51:00.310
by
council or by law, this would be the sort

00:51:00.310 --> 00:51:04.350
of thing where
you would write in saying that essentially

00:51:04.350 --> 00:51:08.060
the tax rate
is determined by a calculation of a GDP or

00:51:08.060 --> 00:51:09.450
some portion
of it?

00:51:09.450 --> 00:51:12.900
How do you --
&gt;&gt;Tomas: You can have a Swedish model

00:51:12.900 --> 00:51:15.030
here where you have high expenditures and
high taxes.

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:17.710
No problem, as long as you don't do deficits.

00:51:17.710 --> 00:51:20.560
&gt;&gt;Male #5: What is the definition of how the
adjustments are made?

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:22.680
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Same way it's done every year.

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:24.630
Every
year we determine this year we're going to

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:26.050
have that
level of deficit.

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:31.710
And we will -- and yeah, we'll have
to have more anti-cyclical taxes or some sort

00:51:31.710 --> 00:51:33.080
of
anti-cyclical expenditures.

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:34.080
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Okay.

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:36.810
So at this point the adjustment of
the anti-cyclical component.

00:51:36.810 --> 00:51:37.810
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: Yes.

00:51:37.810 --> 00:51:38.950
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Taxes.

00:51:38.950 --> 00:51:44.980
So every year you'd have your base
tax then every year there'd be -- or anti-cyclical

00:51:44.980 --> 00:51:45.980
tax
and then --

00:51:45.980 --> 00:51:46.980
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: For example.

00:51:46.980 --> 00:51:47.980
&gt;&gt;Male #5: -- and how it goes up or down,
depending on

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:48.980
how the GDP wants?

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:51.790
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: And the economy actually does that
itself if it is not disturbed by politician.

00:51:51.790 --> 00:51:54.330
In good
years, you tend to have higher tax revenues

00:51:54.330 --> 00:51:58.240
because
companies collect more taxes, and less unemployed

00:51:58.240 --> 00:51:59.970
so you
don't have to give out that many expenditures.

00:51:59.970 --> 00:52:03.320
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Are there any actual real-life
countries

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:07.070
that divide their tax into components, the
base, plus

00:52:07.070 --> 00:52:10.800
the anti-cyclical, and then do actually adjust
the --

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:12.930
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: You, taxes are that way.

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:16.730
Progressive
taxes are -- in progressive taxation, you

00:52:16.730 --> 00:52:20.170
already have
this incorporated.

00:52:20.170 --> 00:52:25.380
[pause] The more you make, the more you get
taxed.

00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:27.250
That's progressive taxation.

00:52:27.250 --> 00:52:30.940
And if your level
of income decreases, you pay lesser not amount,

00:52:30.940 --> 00:52:33.750
but
also percentage of taxes.

00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:34.930
So you wouldn't have to
change much.

00:52:34.930 --> 00:52:35.930
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Okay.

00:52:35.930 --> 00:52:38.180
So we already have supposedly
progressive taxes here.

00:52:38.180 --> 00:52:39.180
Why doesn't it work for us?

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:40.990
&gt;&gt;TOMAS: The problem is, somebody comes up
--

00:52:40.990 --> 00:52:41.990
okay.

00:52:41.990 --> 00:52:44.300
Let's have a little situation.

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:51.300
[paper flipping] The economy's
growing and your taxes -- your tax rate -- this

00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:52.300
is the
budget.

00:52:52.300 --> 00:52:58.120
Your tax revenues are rising and your
expenditures are decreasing.

00:52:58.120 --> 00:53:03.540
And if you let that be on
some sort of an autopilot, the budget will

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:07.020
go itself
into surplus during good years.

00:53:07.020 --> 00:53:10.520
But, of course, this is
extremely tempting because what does a budget

00:53:10.520 --> 00:53:12.250
surplus mean?

00:53:12.250 --> 00:53:13.440
Is
it already 10:00 o'clock?

00:53:13.440 --> 00:53:16.450
Because this is going to be a
very -- 10:00 o'clock in the evening.

00:53:16.450 --> 00:53:17.450
Just a joke.

00:53:17.450 --> 00:53:20.580
This is going to be perverse.

00:53:20.580 --> 00:53:25.080
Imagine you're running an
economy where you gather -- collect more taxes

00:53:25.080 --> 00:53:27.870
than you
give in expenditures.

00:53:27.870 --> 00:53:28.870
What is the temptation?

00:53:28.870 --> 00:53:31.490
The
temptation of course is if you're right wing,

00:53:31.490 --> 00:53:35.191
decrease
taxes immediately, kick the automatic tendency

00:53:35.191 --> 00:53:38.900
of an
economy to stabilize itself, kick it in the

00:53:38.900 --> 00:53:40.930
-- in the --
where do you kick people here in America?

00:53:40.930 --> 00:53:44.330
Kick it in
the right knee.

00:53:44.330 --> 00:53:50.180
[chuckles] And the tendency of a left-wing
politician is to increase expenditures immediately.

00:53:50.180 --> 00:53:53.800
So
just letting that, you know, resisting the

00:53:53.800 --> 00:53:57.500
temptation
like when Odyssey was going in the island

00:53:57.500 --> 00:54:03.480
of the sirens, bind
the hands, close the ears, which is, by the

00:54:03.480 --> 00:54:04.480
way, what
Fed is doing.

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:07.740
Fed is not supposed to -- or central
banks are not supposed to care for political

00:54:07.740 --> 00:54:08.740
cycle.

00:54:08.740 --> 00:54:10.270
Whether there's elections or not, we don't
care.

00:54:10.270 --> 00:54:13.910
We are
just listening to keeping the monetary supply

00:54:13.910 --> 00:54:16.640
-- I mean
keeping the inflation stable.

00:54:16.640 --> 00:54:18.150
Low and stable.

00:54:18.150 --> 00:54:22.770
So
Finland did this.

00:54:22.770 --> 00:54:26.720
They had more tax revenue than they
gave out.

00:54:26.720 --> 00:54:29.490
This is why they were able to decrease their
taxes.

00:54:29.490 --> 00:54:36.230
Yet, having a level of taxation is huge, close
to 50 percent of GDPs being taxed.

00:54:36.230 --> 00:54:38.470
So that is, of
course, that is a political decision of a

00:54:38.470 --> 00:54:42.590
nation: Do
you want to be America with low taxes or Finland

00:54:42.590 --> 00:54:44.360
with
high taxes and high expenditures?

00:54:44.360 --> 00:54:49.420
That's fine, only
don't cheat.

00:54:49.420 --> 00:54:50.940
So this is democratic.

00:54:50.940 --> 00:54:53.250
I think this is
absolutely democratic.

